Fixed input parameters of 'yarp_idl_to_dir()'. The parsing of these parameters based on the ordering has been deprecated
(refer to 'yarp/tests/yarpidl_rosmsg/demo/CMakeLists.txt'). The new interface
identifies the inputs through tags (SOURCES_VAR, HEADERS_VAR, ...) and is
defined as:

yarp_idl_to_dir(INPUT_FILES ${IDL_FILES}
                OUTPUT_DIR "${generated_libs_dir}"
                SOURCES_VAR IDL_GEN_SRCS
                HEADERS_VAR IDL_GEN_HDRS
                INCLUDE_DIRS_VAR IDL_INCLUDE_DIRS
                THRIFT_INCLUDE_PREFIX
                THRIFT_NO_NAMESPACE_PREFIX)

[TorqueBalancing] Added option to load torque PID gains from configuration It is now possible to add at configuration file the possibility to load PID gains for the low level torque control.
A first use is to load a single set of gains. In this case, if no other options are specified, this gains are used for the duration of the module. During module closure the original gains are applied.
This should allow to launch torque balancing with different set of gains depending on the application (single foot, yoga) thus solving the last obstacle to do torquebalancing on the new ethernet robots.

A different use case is the possibility to load different set of gains at startup. It is then possible to switch between gains by using a newly introduced RPC command.
Further debug is need before considering a run-time switch of the gains, so this feature should be considere EXPERIMENTAL

[TorqueBalancing] fixes reference generator This commit fixes a BIG issue with the smoothing reference generator: the Ts parameter was passed in milliseconds instead of seconds.

In the mean time it added support to obtain velocity and acceleration from the smoothing generator (currently not used).
Also added a constant reader.
Fixed some warnings
Fixed also an issue with the impedance generator: because the generator simply outputs a reference (so it is not a controller), when it is activated the smoother starts from 0.
Without smoothing this would not have been a problem, but the smoother in this way starts from zero and in T time it reaches 90% of the reference, which is not the desired behaviour.
I now added an option to force the generator to reset the filter to have the same value of the reference, instead of zero.

[TorqueBalancing] Added support to joint reference smoothing By default smoothing is disabled: references are assumed to be already smoothed by the external generator.
Nonetheless it is possible to enable the internal reference smoothing (currently an instance of type MinimumJerk) by adding an option in the configuration file:

Grammar ( :p )
smooth : smooth_option | '(' smooth_option* ')'
smooth_option = '(' type ',' duration ')'
type = string
duration = double

Currently the only type allowed is the string "joints".

Example of the use of the grammar:
smooth ("joints", 1.0)

Solution of the â€œforceâ€ system is now done explicitly with the truncated pseudoinverse instead of the solve method of JacobiSVD. Explicitly passing the svd decomposition to the pseudoinverse function thus avoiding dynamic allocation (at least of the decomposition object)

About solving the â€œforceâ€ system:
Newer version (the devel one) of Eigen support an explicit threshold which can be set on the decomposition object thus avoiding to compute (explicitly) the SVD.
Because we are limited to 3.2.x (at least for now)  which does not have this function we compute the SVD.

Improved debugging information and checked code with cppcheck for potential memory leaks or style errors. Also permanently fixed the problem of improper closure of the module, by which even though Simulink wouldn't crash after several runs, conflicts among yarp ports could happen because reentrancy was not handled properly during termination. This was due to the fact that the counter variable that controls reentrancy was not being set back to zero after the simulation stopped. Stopping a simulation in Simulink doesn't imply reloading of the mex library, thus static variables keep their last values

Particularly FourthCOMController is the most complete version of the COM controller including contact constraints, velocity saturation, a mask to globally set the robot name and simulation rate. The very same controller was tested on both the simulator and real platform at 10ms. Some issues still need to be addressed regarding the feedforward term. Note; Gains for this controller vary from those used with the simulator and are actually much smaller than those in SecondCOMController, which might be due not only to the use of the real robot but also to the Damped pseudoinverse which was being computed wrongly in the previous version of the model.

a peculiarity of iCub's structure and it is necessary to make the
sensors/motors structure match the kinematic/dynamic model of the robot.
